      "message": "Just noticed something I overlooked: calls like this (and 5 or 6 more below) are not going to behave the same way across different compilers.  The order of evaluation of function arguments is not defined by C++, and different compilers do actually evaluate the arguments in different orders (iirc, GCC first-\u003elast, Clang last-\u003efirst, don\u0027t remember MSVC).\n\nIf fuzz-\u003enextScalar() returns 5.0f then 6.0f, GCC would call m-\u003esetAll(5.0f, 6.0f, ...) where Clang would call m-\u003esetAll(..., 6.0f, 5.0f).\n\nThis is probably as good a reason as any to switch next() from T next() to void next(T*).  If next() doesn\u0027t return a value, it can\u0027t possibly be misused this way.",
